<subSubSection pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="63.[189,454,1085,1111]" box="[189,454,1085,1111]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,454,1085,1111]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,454,1085,1111]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="63.[187,1399,1132,1301]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
The presence of for the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1822" box="[532,644,1132,1158]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[532,644,1132,1158]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Cheilosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
unusual characters such as pale yellowish-brownish body colour, the colour pattern of frons (
<figureCitation box="[500,605,1167,1194]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="64.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[190,1385,792,1886]" captionTargetId="figure-157@64.[189,1398,708,1889]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Fig. 34. Cheilosia insolita sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (CNC). A. Head, anterior view. B. Head, dorsal view. C. Mid leg, anterior view. D. Tip of wing. E. Antenna, lateral view of pedicel and basoflagellomere. Scale bars indicated in drawings." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6840039" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6840039/files/figure.png" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Fig. 34B</figureCitation>
), and a whitish stigma of wing, distinguishes 
<taxonomicName authority="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls, 2022" authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[1123,1243,1167,1194]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insolita" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1123,1243,1167,1194]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">C. insolita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1248,1337,1168,1194]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
from all other congeners. The taxon is here placed as incertae sedis within the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1822" box="[1117,1229,1203,1229]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1117,1229,1203,1229]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Cheilosia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(meaning that the subgeneric placement is unclear) while no male specimen is available for study, and the structures of male genitalia provides critical characteristics for establishing a subgeneric rank of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="63" pageNumber="64" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="63.[189,324,1340,1366]" box="[189,324,1340,1366]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1340,1366]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1340,1366]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="63.[189,1398,1387,1448]" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">
The specific epithet is from the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[632,731,1387,1413]" italics="true" pageId="63" pageNumber="64">insolitus</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘unusual, rare’, referring to the unusual colour of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
